Here's a pass at more clarity on this screen. The one scenario not shown is a failed fixity check. In my mind, that would look similar to the "Not tested yet // [Test manually]()" note/link, but would read "Failed // [Fix the problem]()".

We discussed this together. It might be nice to say why it's not preservered, maybe say "Derivative files are not preserved" or something like that.

The success date formatting could match last motified.

It will be good to have indication of what happens when I click "test manually" -- assuming this enqueues a fixity job, we may need to look into whether it's realistic to implement an "in progress" display. comments.body: @sandbergja suggested we implement https://stackoverflow.com/questions/52973639/force-limit-parameter-to-be-set-in-ansible/54578930#54578930 as a first step toward bulletproofing.

I like these ideas to require a limit as a first step, and to only run on the inactive host. I think it would be good to just stay there for a while and see if we feel burdened by the manual step of then switching the active host and running it again. It might be nice to not have that part automated, in case something didn't go as planned.
Per discussion today we'll include more of the `orphan` groups. See https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/inventory/all_projects/_orphans.
